id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"connector\":{\"kind\":\"builtin\",\"name\":\"claude-code\"},\"role\":\"reviewer\",\"resolved_selection\":{\"skills\":[],\"depth\":\"standard\",\"invocation_options\":{}},\"resolved_from\":{\"source\":\"explicit\"}}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":24,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:25.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"relay.request\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"request_payload_hash\":\"e0afb7784db0114a9aeae5b8fd1cba24a1ef250c10374e7da0b9a17fc41878bf\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":25,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:26.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"relay.receipt\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"cli_version\":\"proof-stub\",\"receipt_id\":\"proof-build-review\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":26,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:27.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"relay.result\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"result_report_hash\":\"ac6dd082fe7171aad8ecacf7641946cfed6cb24c04f6ecae6701a0cfee371772\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":27,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:28.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"relay.completed\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"verdict\":\"accept\",\"duration_ms\":1,\"result_path\":\"reports/relay/build-review.result.json\",\"receipt_path\":\"reports/relay/build-review.receipt.txt\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":28,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:29.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"check.evaluated\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"check_kind\":\"result_verdict\",\"outcome\":\"pass\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":29,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:30.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"step.completed\",\"step_id\":\"review-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"route_taken\":\"pass\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":30,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:31.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"step.entered\",\"step_id\":\"close-step\",\"attempt\":1}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":31,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:32.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"step.report_written\",\"step_id\":\"close-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"report_path\":\"reports/build-result.json\",\"report_schema\":\"build.result@v1\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":32,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:33.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"step.completed\",\"step_id\":\"close-step\",\"attempt\":1,\"route_taken\":\"pass\"}\n+{\"schema_version\":1,\"sequence\":33,\"recorded_at\":\"2026-04-29T18:00:34.000Z\",\"run_id\":\"44444444-4444-4444-4444-444444444402\",\"kind\":\"run.closed\",\"outcome\":\"complete\"}\ndiff --git a/evals/verdict-correctness/README.md b/evals/verdict-correctness/README.md\nindex 6e79ef1..87b0ce5 100644\n--- a/evals/verdict-correctness/README.md\n+++ b/evals/verdict-correctness/README.md\n@@ -13,19 +13,38 @@ claude-code with `--judge claude-code`), and check whether the\n reviewer's verdict surfaced the planted defect in `objections` or\n `missed_angles`.\n \n-Defect catch rate = caught / (caught + missed). Errors are excluded from\n-the denominator. Per-defect rates expose which failure modes the\n-reviewer is good at catching and which it lets through.\n+Defect catch rate = caught / (caught + missed). Errors and skips are\n+excluded from the denominator. If no defect case was scored, the report\n+renders catch rate as `n/a` instead of `0.0%`. Per-defect rates expose\n+which failure modes the reviewer is good at catching and which it lets\n+through.\n \n ## Defect taxonomy\n \n-| ID | Property the reviewer should be guarding |\n-| --- | --- |\n-| `fabricated-evidence-ref` | Evidence groundedness — citations should resolve. |\n-| `stripped-success-condition-alignment` | Alignment justification, not a vacuous restatement. |\n-| `wrong-subject` | Subject fidelity — compose subject must match the brief. |\n-| `added-false-certainty` | Epistemic calibration — claims should not exceed the evidence (no overclaiming). |\n-| `internal-contradiction` | Internal consistency — the recommendation should not negate itself. |\n+| ID | Suite | Property the reviewer should be guarding |\n+| --- | --- | --- |\n+| `fabricated-evidence-ref` | smoke | Evidence groundedness — citations should resolve. |\n+| `stripped-success-condition-alignment` | smoke | Alignment justification, not a vacuous restatement. |\n+| `wrong-subject` | smoke | Subject fidelity — compose subject must match the brief. |\n+| `added-false-certainty` | smoke | Epistemic calibration — claims should not exceed the evidence (no overclaiming). |\n+| `internal-contradiction` | smoke | Internal consistency — the recommendation should not negate itself. |\n+| `plausible-missing-evidence-ref` | subtle | Evidence groundedness when the bad citation looks like a plausible sibling path. |\n+| `generic-success-condition-alignment` | subtle | Alignment justification when the text sounds plausible but could fit any brief. |\n+| `soft-false-certainty` | subtle | Epistemic calibration when the overclaim is mild, not a loud \"no remaining risks\" claim. |\n+\n+The smoke suite is the old obvious-defect guard. The subtle suite is the\n+newer discrimination suite; it should be allowed to score below 100%.\n+\n+## Source corpus\n+\n+Baseline runs use `source-manifest.json`, a committed list of stable\n+historical explore review requests copied under\n+`fixtures/source-requests/`. `--source-mode manifest` is the default and\n+reports `baseline: true`.\n+\n+Use `--source-mode discover` for ad hoc local exploration. Discovery scans\n+`.circuit-next/runs` in deterministic path order, but reports are labeled\n+non-baseline and should not be compared against manifest runs.\n \n See `defect-taxonomy.ts` for the planting functions and\n `scorer.ts` for the per-defect catch heuristics.\n@@ -41,10 +60,22 @@ npm run build\n Then:\n \n ```bash\n-# Full run with default judge (codex): every explore review request,\n-# every defect, plus controls.\n+# Baseline smoke run with default judge (codex): manifest sources,\n+# smoke defects, plus controls.\n node --experimental-strip-types evals/verdict-correctness/index.ts\n \n+# Subtle suite: harder defects meant to avoid 100% ceiling effects.\n+node --experimental-strip-types evals/verdict-correctness/index.ts \\\n+  --suite subtle\n+\n+# All defects, including smoke and subtle.\n+node --experimental-strip-types evals/verdict-correctness/index.ts \\\n+  --suite all\n+\n+# Ad hoc local source discovery. Reports from this mode are non-baseline.\n+node --experimental-strip-types evals/verdict-correctness/index.ts \\\n+  --source-mode discover --suite subtle\n+\n # Cross-judge arm: same prompts, claude-code as the reviewer-under-test.\n # Use this to check whether catch-rate findings survive a different\n # model family or were artifacts of self-grading bias.\n@@ -67,6 +98,14 @@ Outputs land in `evals/verdict-correctness/results/<timestamp>-<judge>/`:\n - `summary.json` — aggregated metrics\n - `report.md` — human-readable report\n \n+Reports include suite, source mode, baseline/non-baseline status, source\n+counts, skips, possible control false positives, catch rate, runtime, and\n+errors. A skipped planter means the defect could not be injected into\n+that source compose; it is not a connector or model failure.\n+Environment failures, such as sandboxed cache/home-directory write\n+errors, are reported separately from connector/model failures so they do\n+not look like reviewer misses.\n+\n ## Cost and wallclock\n \n Each case is one connector subprocess call.\ndiff --git a/evals/verdict-correctness/RESULTS.md b/evals/verdict-correctness/RESULTS.md\nindex f661a2f..e6db97d 100644\n--- a/evals/verdict-correctness/RESULTS.md\n+++ b/evals/verdict-correctness/RESULTS.md\n@@ -4,6 +4,127 @@ Internal eval. Goal: measure whether the explore-flow review step catches\n mechanically-planted defects in compose outputs, and use the result to find\n real product gaps.\n \n+## Step 1 harness update (2026-05-09) — reproducible + subtle suite\n+\n+The eval harness now has two suite modes:\n+\n+- `smoke` keeps the original obvious-defect taxonomy and remains the\n+  default regression guard.\n+- `subtle` adds three harder defects:\n+  `plausible-missing-evidence-ref`,\n+  `generic-success-condition-alignment`, and `soft-false-certainty`.\n+\n+Baseline source selection now comes from `source-manifest.json` and\n+committed fixture copies under `fixtures/source-requests/` instead of\n+whatever `.circuit-next/runs` happens to contain. Ad hoc local discovery\n+is still available with `--source-mode discover`, but those reports are\n+labeled non-baseline.\n+\n+Skipped planters are now first-class outcomes rather than connector\n+errors. Control cases also report possible scorer false positives\n+without failing the suite automatically.\n+\n+Small probe:\n+\n+```bash\n+node --experimental-strip-types evals/verdict-correctness/index.ts \\\n+  --suite subtle --max-composes 3 --dry-run\n+```\n+\n+Result: built 12 cases from 3 manifest sources: 3 controls plus 3\n+subtle defects per source.\n+\n+Live probe attempted with the same arguments. It exercised report\n+generation, but all 12 connector calls failed in the sandbox before any\n+model verdict was returned because Codex could not write its\n+home-directory skills/model caches:\n+\n+```text\n+codex subprocess exited with code 1; stderr[:500]=WARNING: proceeding,\n+even though we could not update PATH: Operation not permitted (os error 1)\n+```\n+\n+Generated local report:\n+`evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T04-21-12-395Z-codex/report.md`.\n+This run is useful as a harness/error-reporting check, but not as a\n+catch-rate signal. A real subtle-suite baseline still needs to be run in\n+an environment where the connector can access its normal cache.\n+\n+Follow-up hardening on 2026-05-09:\n+\n+- `npm run verify` passed after the harness changes and related generated\n+  runtime updates.\n+- The subtle 3-source dry run builds 12 cases deterministically.\n+- The full subtle manifest dry run builds 32 cases from 8 manifest\n+  sources. One `plausible-missing-evidence-ref` case is skipped because\n+  the source compose has no evidence refs to mutate; this is reported as\n+  a skipped planter, not a connector/model error.\n+- A sandboxed live Codex run still fails before any reviewer verdict is\n+  returned because Codex cannot write its home-directory skills/model\n+  caches. Rescoring that run with the current harness classifies all 12\n+  failures as `environment_error`, with `catch_rate: null` rendered as\n+  `n/a`.\n+- An unsandboxed rerun was not performed because the approval reviewer\n+  rejected it: the run would export repo-derived prompts to the external\n+  Codex service. A real live baseline therefore needs explicit approval\n+  in an environment where that export is acceptable.\n+\n+Full-shell live probes later on 2026-05-09 made the subtle suite\n+interpretable. The first raw live run reported `4/9` with one possible\n+control false positive, but manual audit showed several scorer false\n+negatives: the reviewer had caught plausible missing evidence refs with\n+phrases such as \"not included in the provided run reads\" and \"not\n+resolvable from the provided reads.\" The scorer was tightened around\n+those semantic objections, and `rescore.ts` now recomputes controls\n+instead of carrying stale possible false positives forward.\n+\n+Rescored live-run summary with the final scorer:\n+\n+| Run folder | Scored catch rate | Errors | Possible control false positives | Reading |\n+| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | --- |\n+| `2026-05-09T15-08-51-911Z-codex` | 8/9 = 88.9% | 0 | 0 | Evidence refs 3/3, generic alignment 3/3, soft false certainty 2/3. |\n+| `2026-05-09T15-25-37-496Z-codex` | 7/8 = 87.5% | 1 connector timeout | 0 | Same pattern, excluding one timed-out evidence-ref case. |\n+| `2026-05-09T15-34-30-779Z-codex` | 7/9 = 77.8% | 0 | 0 | Clean run; evidence refs 3/3, generic alignment 3/3, soft false certainty 1/3. |\n+\n+The useful product signal is not the original raw `44.4%` terminal\n+number. The stable signal after scorer repair is:\n+\n+- `plausible-missing-evidence-ref` is consistently caught.\n+- `generic-success-condition-alignment` is consistently caught.\n+- `soft-false-certainty` remains the active weakness; the reviewer\n+  sometimes flags the no-follow-up-readiness overclaim, but often only\n+  flags adjacent evidence/calibration issues.\n+\n+Latest local artifacts:\n+\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T15-08-51-911Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T15-25-37-496Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T15-34-30-779Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+\n+Full manifest baseline and prompt fix follow-up:\n+\n+| Run folder | Scope | Scored catch rate | Errors | Skips | Possible control false positives | Reading |\n+| --- | --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | --- |\n+| `2026-05-09T16-07-12-000Z-codex` | all 8 manifest sources, before prompt fix | 20/23 = 87.0% | 0 | 1 | 0 | Evidence refs 7/7, generic alignment 8/8, soft false certainty 5/8. |\n+| `2026-05-09T16-50-01-104Z-codex` | first 3 manifest sources, after prompt fix | 9/9 = 100.0% | 0 | 0 | 1 | The known soft-certainty miss on `61938f39` was caught after the review hint change. |\n+| `2026-05-09T16-58-12-635Z-codex` | all 8 manifest sources, after prompt fix | 23/23 = 100.0% | 0 | 1 | 2 | Evidence refs 7/7, generic alignment 8/8, soft false certainty 8/8. |\n+\n+The review hint now explicitly tells the reviewer to flag mild readiness\n+overclaims when the compose also says proof, validation, repo inspection,\n+or follow-up investigation is still needed. The post-fix probe shows the\n+desired movement on `soft-false-certainty`: all three sampled planted\n+defects were caught, then the full manifest post-fix run caught every\n+scored planted defect. The possible control false positives are real\n+latent readiness issues in unmodified controls, not scorer artifacts; the\n+reviewer objected that some controls treat thin, unverified evidence as\n+more actionable than their own caveats support.\n+\n+Latest post-fix artifacts:\n+\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T16-07-12-000Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T16-50-01-104Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+- `evals/verdict-correctness/results/2026-05-09T16-58-12-635Z-codex/rescored-report.md`\n+\n ## Iteration 2 (2026-05-08, post-fix + 2 min timeout + planter fix) — headline\n \n **Catch rate: 37/37 = 100%** (catches / catches + misses, errors excluded).\ndiff --git a/evals/verdict-correctness/defect-taxonomy.ts b/evals/verdict-correctness/defect-taxonomy.ts\nindex ad699fd..89376b2 100644\n--- a/evals/verdict-correctness/defect-taxonomy.ts\n+++ b/evals/verdict-correctness/defect-taxonomy.ts\n@@ -4,10 +4,14 @@\n //\n // Defects are designed to break properties the reviewer is supposed to\n // guard:\n-//   - evidence groundedness (fabricated-evidence-ref)\n-//   - success-condition justification (stripped-success-condition-alignment)\n+//   - evidence groundedness (fabricated-evidence-ref,\n+//     plausible-missing-evidence-ref)\n+//   - success-condition justification\n+//     (stripped-success-condition-alignment,\n+//     generic-success-condition-alignment)\n //   - subject fidelity (wrong-subject)\n-//   - epistemic calibration (added-false-certainty)\n+//   - epistemic calibration (added-false-certainty,\n+//     soft-false-certainty)\n //   - internal consistency (internal-contradiction)\n //\n // Why added-false-certainty replaced the older removed-uncertainty mutator